    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-05-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-05-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="115"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d115">
                <head>115. Memorandum of a Conversation, Department of State, Washington, May 1,
                        1956<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d115fn1">Source: Department of State,
                        Central Files, 460.119/5–156. Secret. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_MADII1">MacArthur</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1956-05-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 1, 1956</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Control of Shipments of Strategic Items to Communist Countries</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>The Secretary</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MADII1">MacArthur</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_C1">C</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Sir <persName corresp="#p_MSR1">Roger Makins</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Sir <persName>Hubert Graves</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Sir <persName corresp="#p_MSR1">Roger</persName> said he had originally expected
                    to have some detailed instructions this morning to discuss with the Secretary
                    regarding strategic controls on shipments of items to Communist countries.
                    However, the recent message from the President had added a new element to the
                    situation, and Foreign Secretary <persName corresp="#p_LS1">Lloyd</persName> had
                    informed Sir <persName corresp="#p_MSR1">Roger</persName> that in the light of
                    the President’s message he would look forward to discussing this subject with
                    the Secretary in Paris.</p>
                <p>Sir <persName corresp="#p_MSR1">Roger</persName> said he thought the general
                    approach taken by the President with respect to the <gloss target="#t_CHINCOM1"
                        >Chincom</gloss> controls was helpful. With respect to copper wire shipments
                    from the <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> to the Soviet Union, the <gloss
                        target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> was willing to review this situation, but Sir
                        <persName corresp="#p_MSR1">Roger</persName> emphasized that it was not
                    politically possible, in the light of the recent Bulganin–Khrushchev visit and
                    the heavy play the Soviets had made to increase trade with the <gloss
                        target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>, for the <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> as a
                    result of such review simply to add additional controls on the shipment of
                    copper wire.</p>
                <p>The Secretary said he understood the situation and the political difficulties
                    which the British Government would have if, when the Soviets were trying to
                    reduce the <gloss target="#t_COCOM1">Cocom</gloss> list, the only result were an
                    increase in this list. He thought, however, that it might well be possible to
                    find two or three items on which the controls could be lowered. The Secretary
                    pointed out again the importance we attached to reducing the shipments of copper
                    wire for military … reasons, and Sir <persName corresp="#p_MSR1"
                        >Roger</persName> said he had explained in detail our views to
                        <persName>Walter Monckton</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d115fn2">British Minister of Defense.</note> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_TP1">Peter Thorneycroft</persName> when he, Sir <persName
                        corresp="#p_MSR1">Roger</persName>, visited London last week.</p>
                <p>It was left that the Secretary and Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LS1"
                        >Lloyd</persName> would discuss this matter further in Paris when they met
                    on May 3.</p>
            </div>
